# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: orthogonal-polynomials
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] The **Chebyshev polynomials** are two sequences of orthogonal polynomials related to the cosine and sine functions, notated as $T_{n}(x)$ and $U_{n}(x)$ .
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] That these expressions define polynomials in $\cos \theta$ is not obvious at first sight but can be shown using de Moivre's formula (see below).
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] The Chebyshev polynomials *Tn* are polynomials with the largest possible leading coefficient whose absolute value on the interval [−1, 1] is bounded by 1.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] They are also the "extremal" polynomials for many other properties.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] In 1952, Cornelius Lanczos showed that the Chebyshev polynomials are important in approximation theory for the solution of linear systems; the roots of *Tn*(*x*), which are also called *Chebyshev nodes*, are used as matching points for optimizing polynomial interpolation.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] The resulting interpolation polynomial minimizes the problem of Runge's phenomenon and provides an approximation that is close to the best polynomial approximation to a continuous function under the maximum norm, also called the "minimax" criterion.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] This approximation leads directly to the method of Clenshaw–Curtis quadrature.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] These polynomials were named after Pafnuty Chebyshev.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] The letter T is used because of the alternative transliterations of the name *Chebyshev* as *Tchebycheff*, *Tchebyshev* (French) or *Tschebyschow* (German).
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] The Chebyshev polynomials of the first and second kind can be defined as the unique polynomials satisfying $T_{n}(\cos \theta )=\cos(n\theta )\quad$ and $U_{n}(\cos \theta )={\frac {{\sin }{\big (}(n+1)\theta {\big )}}{\sin \theta }},$ for *n* = 0, 1, 2, 3, ….
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] Chebyshev polynomials can also be defined in this form when studying trigonometric polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] The real part of the other side is a polynomial in $\cos x$ and $\sin x$ , in which all powers of $\sin x$ are even and thus replaceable through the identity $\cos ^{2}x+\sin ^{2}x=1$ .
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] By the same reasoning, $\sin nx$ is the imaginary part of the polynomial, in which all powers of $\sin x$ are odd and thus, if one factor of $\sin x$ is factored out, the remaining factors can be replaced to create a polynomial of degree $n-1$ in $\cos x$ .
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] This relationship is used in the Chebyshev spectral method of solving differential equations.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] where integrals are considered as principal value.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] An explicit form of the Chebyshev polynomial in terms of monomials $\textstyle x^{k}$ can be obtained as follows.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] Chebyshev polynomials of odd order have odd symmetry and therefore contain only odd powers of x .
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] A Chebyshev polynomial of either kind with degree n has n different simple roots, called **Chebyshev roots**, in the interval [−1, 1].
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] The roots of the Chebyshev polynomial of the first kind are sometimes called Chebyshev nodes because they are used as *nodes* in polynomial interpolation.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] Thus these polynomials have only two finite critical values, the defining property of Shabat polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] The derivatives of the polynomials can be less than straightforward.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] Since $T_{m}(x)$ is divisible by x if m is odd, it follows that $T_{mn}(x)$ is divisible by $T_{n}(x)$ if m is odd.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] Both $T_{n}$ and $U_{n}$ form a sequence of orthogonal polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] These orthogonality properties follow from the fact that the Chebyshev polynomials solve the Chebyshev differential equations ${\begin{aligned}(1-x^{2})T_{n}''-xT_{n}'+n^{2}T_{n}&=0,\\[1ex](1-x^{2})U_{n}''-3xU_{n}'+n(n+2)U_{n}&=0,\end{aligned}}$ which are Sturm–Liouville differential equations.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] It is a general feature of such differential equations that there is a distinguished orthonormal set of solutions.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] For any given $n\geq 1$ , among the polynomials of degree n with leading coefficient 1 (monic polynomials): $f(x)={\frac {1}{2^{n-1}}}T_{n}(x)$ is the one of which the maximal absolute value on the interval [−1, 1] is minimal.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] Let's assume that $w_{n}(x)$ is a polynomial of degree n with leading coefficient 1 with maximal absolute value on the interval [−1, 1] less than 1 / 2*n* − 1.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] From the intermediate value theorem, *fn*(*x*) has at least n roots.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] However, this is impossible, as *fn*(*x*) is a polynomial of degree *n* − 1, so the fundamental theorem of algebra implies it has at most *n* − 1 roots.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] By the equioscillation theorem, among all the polynomials of degree ≤ *n*, the polynomial f minimizes ‖ *f* ‖∞ on [−1, 1] if and only if there are *n* + 2 points −1 ≤ *x*0 < *x*1 < ⋯ < *x**n* + 1 ≤ 1 such that | *f*(*xi*)| = ‖ *f* ‖∞.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] Of course, the null polynomial on the interval [−1, 1] can be approximated by itself and minimizes the ∞-norm.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] Above, however, | *f* | reaches its maximum only *n* + 1 times because we are searching for the best polynomial of degree *n* ≥ 1 (therefore the theorem evoked previously cannot be used).
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] The curves given by *y* = *T**n*(*x*), or equivalently, by the parametric equations *y* = *T**n*(cos *θ*) = cos *nθ*, *x* = cos *θ*, are a special case of Lissajous curves with frequency ratio equal to n.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] This sum is called a **Chebyshev series** or a **Chebyshev expansion**.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] Since a Chebyshev series is related to a Fourier cosine series through a change of variables, all of the theorems, identities, etc. that apply to Fourier series have a Chebyshev counterpart.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] The Chebfun software package supports function manipulation based on their expansion in the Chebyshev basis.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] Consider the Chebyshev expansion of log(1 + *x*).
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] One can find the coefficients *an* either through the application of an inner product or by the discrete orthogonality condition.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] For any N, these approximate coefficients provide an exact approximation to the function at xk with a controlled error between those points.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] The exact coefficients are obtained with *N* = ∞, thus representing the function exactly at all points in [−1,1].
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] The rate of convergence depends on the function and its smoothness.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] The partial sums of: $f(x)=\sum _{n=0}^{\infty }a_{n}T_{n}(x)$ are very useful in the approximation of various functions and in the solution of differential equations (see spectral method).
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] Two common methods for determining the coefficients an are through the use of the inner product as in Galerkin's method and through the use of collocation which is related to interpolation.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] As an interpolant, the N coefficients of the (*N* − 1)st partial sum are usually obtained on the Chebyshev–Gauss–Lobatto points (or Lobatto grid), which results in minimum error and avoids Runge's phenomenon associated with a uniform grid.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] An arbitrary polynomial of degree N can be written in terms of the Chebyshev polynomials of the first kind.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] Polynomials in Chebyshev form can be evaluated using the Clenshaw algorithm.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] Polynomials denoted $C_{n}(x)$ and $S_{n}(x)$ closely related to Chebyshev polynomials are sometimes used.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] Horadam called the polynomials $C_{n}(x)$ **Vieta–Lucas polynomials** and denoted them $v_{n}(x)$ .
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] He called the polynomials $S_{n}(x)$ **Vieta–Fibonacci polynomials** and denoted them $V_{n}(x)$ .
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] All of these polynomials have 1 as their leading coefficient.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] Lists of both sets of polynomials are given in Viète's *Opera Mathematica*, Chapter IX, Theorems VI and VII.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] The Vieta–Lucas and Vieta–Fibonacci polynomials of real argument are, up to a power of i and a shift of index in the case of the latter, equal to Lucas and Fibonacci polynomials *L**n* and *F**n* of imaginary argument.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] When the argument of the Chebyshev polynomial satisfies 2*x* − 1 ∈ [−1, 1] the argument of the shifted Chebyshev polynomial satisfies *x* ∈ [0, 1].
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] Similarly, one can define shifted polynomials for generic intervals [*a*, *b*].
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] Around 1990 the terms "third-kind" and "fourth-kind" came into use in connection with Chebyshev polynomials, although the polynomials denoted by these terms had an earlier development under the name **airfoil polynomials**.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] They coincide with the Dirichlet kernel.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] It is easier to discuss this detail by first examining the factorization of the Vieta-Lucas and Vieta-Fibonacci polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] The polynomials $\Psi _{n}(x)$ may be referred to as cyclotomic pre-polynomials, since the cyclotomic polynomials can be obtained from them via a well-defined mapping.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] An obvious property of the mapping $P_{n}(x)\rightarrow x^{n}P_{n}{\left(x+{\frac {1}{x}}\right)}$ applicable to any polynomial $P_{n}(x)$ of degree n is that it maps the product of two or more polynomials to the product of the images of the individual polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] From the irreducibility of the polynomials $\Phi _{n}(x)$ it follows that the polynomials $\Psi _{n}(x)$ are also irreducible.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] Some applications rely on Chebyshev polynomials but may be unable to accommodate the lack of a root at zero, which rules out the use of standard Chebyshev polynomials for these kinds of applications.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] Even order Chebyshev filter designs using equally terminated passive networks are an example of this.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] However, even order Chebyshev polynomials may be modified to move the lowest roots down to zero while still maintaining the desirable Chebyshev equi-ripple effect.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] Such modified polynomials contain two roots at zero, and may be referred to as even order modified Chebyshev polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] Even order modified Chebyshev polynomials may be created from the Chebyshev nodes in the same manner as standard Chebyshev polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] In the case of even order modified Chebyshev polynomials, the even order modified Chebyshev nodes are used to construct the even order modified Chebyshev polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] For example, the 4th order Chebyshev polynomial from the example above is $X^{4}-X^{2}+.125$ , which by inspection contains no roots of zero.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/chebyshev-polynomials] Creating the polynomial from the even order modified Chebyshev nodes creates a 4th order even order modified Chebyshev polynomial of $X^{4}-.828427X^{2}$ , which by inspection contains two roots at zero, and may be used in applications requiring roots at zero.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] In mathematics, the **classical orthogonal polynomials** are the most widely used orthogonal polynomials: the Hermite polynomials, Laguerre polynomials, Jacobi polynomials (including as a special case the Gegenbauer polynomials, Chebyshev polynomials, and Legendre polynomials).
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] They have many important applications in such areas as mathematical physics (in particular, the theory of random matrices), approximation theory, numerical analysis, and many others.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] Classical orthogonal polynomials appeared in the early 19th century in the works of Adrien-Marie Legendre, who introduced the Legendre polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] In the late 19th century, the study of continued fractions to solve the moment problem by P.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] Stieltjes led to the general notion of orthogonal polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] with to be determined constants $\lambda _{n}\in \mathbb {R}$ .
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] The Wikipedia article Rodrigues' formula has a proof that the polynomials obtained from the Rodrigues' formula obey a differential equation of this form and also derives $\lambda _{n}$ .
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] There are several more general definitions of orthogonal classical polynomials; for example, Andrews & Askey (1985) use the term for all polynomials in the Askey scheme.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] The relations above define $P_{n}$ up to multiplication by a number.
