[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] (We put the "r" in brackets to avoid confusion with an exponent.) *P*[*r*] *n* is a polynomial of degree *n* − *r*.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] In each of these, the numbers *a*, *b*, and *c* depend on *n* and *r*, and are unrelated in the various formulas.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] There are an enormous number of other formulas involving orthogonal polynomials in various ways.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] All of the polynomial sequences arising from the differential equation above are equivalent, under scaling and/or shifting of the domain, and standardizing of the polynomials, to more restricted classes.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] Those restricted classes are exactly "classical orthogonal polynomials".
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] Because all polynomial sequences arising from a differential equation in the manner described above are trivially equivalent to the classical polynomials, the actual classical polynomials are always used.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] The Jacobi-like polynomials, once they have had their domain shifted and scaled so that the interval of orthogonality is [−1, 1], still have two parameters to be determined.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] They are $\alpha$ and $\beta$ in the Jacobi polynomials, written $P_{n}^{(\alpha ,\beta )}$ .
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] Both $\alpha$ and $\beta$ are required to be greater than −1.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] When $\alpha$ and $\beta$ are not equal, these polynomials are not symmetrical about *x* = 0.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] For further details, see Jacobi polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] When one sets the parameters $\alpha$ and $\beta$ in the Jacobi polynomials equal to each other, one obtains the **Gegenbauer** or **ultraspherical** polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] The parameter $\alpha$ is required to be greater than −1/2.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] (Incidentally, the standardization given in the table below would make no sense for *α* = 0 and *n* ≠ 0, because it would set the polynomials to zero.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] All the other classical Jacobi-like polynomials (Legendre, etc.) are special cases of the Gegenbauer polynomials, obtained by choosing a value of $\alpha$ and choosing a standardization.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] For further details, see Gegenbauer polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] For further details, see Legendre polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] The *m* in parentheses (to avoid confusion with an exponent) is a parameter.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] The *m* in brackets denotes the *m*-th derivative of the Legendre polynomial.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] These "polynomials" are misnamed—they are not polynomials when *m* is odd.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] This means that all their local minima and maxima have values of −1 and +1, that is, the polynomials are "level".
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] Because of this, expansion of functions in terms of Chebyshev polynomials is sometimes used for polynomial approximations in computer math libraries.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] Some authors use versions of these polynomials that have been shifted so that the interval of orthogonality is [0, 1] or [−2, 2].
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] For further details, including the expressions for the first few polynomials, see Chebyshev polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] The most general Laguerre-like polynomials, after the domain has been shifted and scaled, are the Associated Laguerre polynomials (also called generalized Laguerre polynomials), denoted $L_{n}^{(\alpha )}$ .
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] There is a parameter $\alpha$ , which can be any real number strictly greater than −1.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] The parameter is put in parentheses to avoid confusion with an exponent.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] This equation arises in quantum mechanics, in the radial part of the solution of the Schrödinger equation for a one-electron atom.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] Physicists often use a definition for the Laguerre polynomials that is larger, by a factor of $(n!)$ , than the definition used here.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] For further details, including the expressions for the first few polynomials, see Laguerre polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] Because the multiplier is proportional to the square root of the weight function, these functions are orthogonal over $(-\infty ,\infty )$ with no weight function.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] The associated Hermite functions arise in many areas of mathematics and physics.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] In quantum mechanics, they are the solutions of Schrödinger's equation for the harmonic oscillator.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] They are also eigenfunctions (with eigenvalue (−*i* *n*) of the continuous Fourier transform.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] Many authors, particularly probabilists, use an alternate definition of the Hermite polynomials, with a weight function of $e^{-x^{2}/2}$ instead of $e^{-x^{2}}$ .
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] For further details, see Hermite polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] There are several conditions that single out the classical orthogonal polynomials from the others.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] The first condition was found by Sonine (and later by Hahn), who showed that (up to linear changes of variable) the classical orthogonal polynomials are the only ones such that their derivatives are also orthogonal polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] Bochner characterized classical orthogonal polynomials in terms of their recurrence relations.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] Tricomi characterized classical orthogonal polynomials as those that have a certain analogue of the Rodrigues formula.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/classical-orthogonal-polynomials] The following table summarises the properties of the classical orthogonal polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/gegenbauer-polynomials] In mathematics, **Gegenbauer polynomials** or **ultraspherical polynomials** *C*(α) *n*(*x*) are orthogonal polynomials on the interval [−1,1] with respect to the weight function (1 − *x*2)*α*–1/2.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/gegenbauer-polynomials] They generalize Legendre polynomials and Chebyshev polynomials, and are special cases of Jacobi polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/gegenbauer-polynomials] They are named after Leopold Gegenbauer.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/gegenbauer-polynomials] A variety of characterizations of the Gegenbauer polynomials are available.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/gegenbauer-polynomials] The Gegenbauer polynomials appear naturally as extensions of Legendre polynomials in the context of potential theory and harmonic analysis.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/gegenbauer-polynomials] When *n* = 3, this gives the Legendre polynomial expansion of the gravitational potential.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/gegenbauer-polynomials] Similar expressions are available for the expansion of the Poisson kernel in a ball.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/gegenbauer-polynomials] It follows that the quantities $C_{k}^{((n-2)/2)}(\mathbf {x} \cdot \mathbf {y} )$ are spherical harmonics, when regarded as a function of **x** only.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/gegenbauer-polynomials] They are, in fact, exactly the zonal spherical harmonics, up to a normalizing constant.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/gegenbauer-polynomials] Gegenbauer polynomials also appear in the theory of positive-definite functions.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/gegenbauer-polynomials] Other asymptotic formulas can be obtained as special cases of asymptotic formulas for the more general Jacobi polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] In mathematics, the **Hermite polynomials** are a classical orthogonal polynomial sequence.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] Hermite polynomials were defined by Pierre-Simon Laplace in 1810, though in scarcely recognizable form, and studied in detail by Pafnuty Chebyshev in 1859.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] Chebyshev's work was overlooked, and they were named later after Charles Hermite, who wrote on the polynomials in 1864, describing them as new.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] They were not new, although Hermite was the first to define the multidimensional polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] Like the other classical orthogonal polynomials, the Hermite polynomials can be defined from several different starting points.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] These are Hermite polynomial sequences of different variances; see the material on variances below.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] The notation $\operatorname {He}$ and H is that used in the standard references.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] The polynomials $\operatorname {He} _{n}$ are sometimes denoted by $H_{n}$ , especially in probability theory, because ${\frac {1}{\sqrt {2\pi }}}e^{-{\frac {x^{2}}{2}}}$ is the probability density function for the normal distribution with expected value 0 and standard deviation 1.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] The probabilist's Hermite polynomials are also called the **monic Hermite polynomials**, because they are monic.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] The nth-order Hermite polynomial is a polynomial of degree n.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] The probabilist's version Hen has leading coefficient 1, while the physicist's version Hn has leading coefficient 2*n*.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] The probabilist polynomials are thus orthogonal with respect to the standard normal probability density function.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] An orthogonal basis for *L*2(**R**, *w*(*x*) *dx*) is a *complete* orthogonal system.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] For an orthogonal system, *completeness* is equivalent to the fact that the 0 function is the only function *f* ∈ *L*2(**R**, *w*(*x*) *dx*) orthogonal to *all* functions in the system.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] Since the linear span of Hermite polynomials is the space of all polynomials, one has to show (in physicist case) that if f satisfies $\int _{-\infty }^{\infty }f(x)x^{n}e^{-x^{2}}\,dx=0$ for every *n* ≥ 0, then *f* = 0.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] The fact then that *F*(*it*) = 0 for every real t means that the Fourier transform of *f*(*x*)*e*−*x*2 is 0, hence f is 0 almost everywhere.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] Variants of the above completeness proof apply to other weights with exponential decay.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] In the Hermite case, it is also possible to prove an explicit identity that implies completeness (see section on the Completeness relation below).
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] An equivalent formulation of the fact that Hermite polynomials are an orthogonal basis for *L*2(**R**, *w*(*x*) *dx*) consists in introducing Hermite *functions* (see below), and in saying that the Hermite functions are an orthonormal basis for *L*2(**R**).
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] The probabilist's Hermite polynomials are solutions of the Sturm–Liouville differential equation $\left(e^{-{\frac {1}{2}}x^{2}}u'\right)'+\lambda e^{-{\frac {1}{2}}x^{2}}u=0,$ where λ is a constant.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] Imposing the boundary condition that u should be polynomially bounded at infinity, the equation has solutions only if λ is a non-negative integer, and the solution is uniquely given by $u(x)=C_{1}\operatorname {He} _{\lambda }(x)$ , where $C_{1}$ denotes a constant.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] Rewriting the differential equation as an eigenvalue problem $L[u]=u''-xu'=-\lambda u,$ the Hermite polynomials $\operatorname {He} _{\lambda }(x)$ may be understood as eigenfunctions of the differential operator $L[u]$ .
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] The general solutions to the above second-order differential equations are in fact linear combinations of both Hermite polynomials and confluent hypergeometric functions of the first kind.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] The conventional Hermite polynomials may also be expressed in terms of confluent hypergeometric functions, see below.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] With more general boundary conditions, the Hermite polynomials can be generalized to obtain more general analytic functions for complex-valued λ.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] An explicit formula of Hermite polynomials in terms of contour integrals (Courant & Hilbert 1989) is also possible.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] These last relations, together with the initial polynomials *H*0(*x*) and *H*1(*x*), can be used in practice to compute the polynomials quickly.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] This equality is valid for all complex values of x and t, and can be obtained by writing the Taylor expansion at x of the entire function *z* → *e*−*z*2 (in the physicist's case).
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] Using this in the sum $\sum _{n=0}^{\infty }H_{n}(x){\frac {t^{n}}{n!}},$ one can evaluate the remaining integral using the calculus of residues and arrive at the desired generating function.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] The moments of the standard normal (with expected value zero) may be read off directly from the relation for even indices: $\operatorname {\mathbb {E} } \left[X^{2n}\right]=(-1)^{n}\operatorname {He} _{2n}(0)=(2n-1)!!,$ where (2*n* − 1)!! is the double factorial.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] The term $\left(1-{\frac {x^{2}}{2n+1}}\right)^{-{\frac {1}{2}}}$ corresponds to the probability of finding a classical particle in a potential well of shape $V(x)={\frac {1}{2}}x^{2}$ at location x , if its total energy is $n+{\frac {1}{2}}$ .
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] This is a general method in semiclassical analysis.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] The semiclassical approximation breaks down near $\pm {\sqrt {2n+1}}$ , the location where the classical particle would be turned back.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] This is a fold catastrophe, at which point the Airy function is needed.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] The Plancherel–Rotach asymptotics method, applied to Hermite polynomials, takes into account the uneven spacing of the zeros near the edges.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] Similar approximations hold for the monotonic and transition regions.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] The physicist's Hermite polynomials evaluated at zero argument *Hn*(0) are called Hermite numbers.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] This gives Mehler's formula when $M={\begin{bmatrix}0&u\\u&0\end{bmatrix}}$ .
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] Foata gave a combinatorial proof while Louck gave a proof via boson quantum mechanics.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] It has a generalization for complex-argument Hermite polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] Let $x_{n,1}>\dots >x_{n,n}$ be the roots of $H_{n}$ in descending order.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] Let $a_{m}$ be the m -th zero of the Airy function $\operatorname {Ai} (x)$ in descending order: $0>a_{1}>a_{2}>\cdots$ .
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] By the symmetry of $H_{n}$ , we need only consider the positive half of its roots.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] See also, and the formulas involving the zeroes of Laguerre polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] This can be constructed by confining n positively charged particles in $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ to the real line, and connecting each particle to the origin by a spring.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] This is also called the **electrostatic model**, and relates to the Coulomb gas interpretation of the eigenvalues of gaussian ensembles.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] As the zeroes specify the polynomial up to scaling, the Stieltjes relation provides an alternative way to uniquely characterize the Hermite polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] The physicist's Hermite polynomials can be expressed as a special case of the parabolic cylinder functions: $H_{n}(x)=2^{n}U\left(-{\tfrac {1}{2}}n,{\tfrac {1}{2}},x^{2}\right)$ in the right half-plane, where *U*(*a*, *b*, *z*) is Tricomi's confluent hypergeometric function.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] The Hermite polynomials can be obtained as the limit of various other polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] Similar to Taylor expansion, some functions are expressible as an infinite sum of Hermite polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] Specifically, if $\int e^{-x^{2}}f(x)^{2}dx<\infty$ , then it has an expansion in the physicist's Hermite polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] The probabilist's Hermite polynomials satisfy the identity $\operatorname {He} _{n}(x)=e^{-{\frac {D^{2}}{2}}}x^{n},$ where D represents differentiation with respect to x, and the exponential is interpreted by expanding it as a power series.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] There are no delicate questions of convergence of this series when it operates on polynomials, since all but finitely many terms vanish.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] Since the formal expression for the Weierstrass transform W is *e**D*2, we see that the Weierstrass transform of (√2)*n**Hen*(⁠*x*/√2⁠) is *xn*.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] Essentially the Weierstrass transform thus turns a series of Hermite polynomials into a corresponding Maclaurin series.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] The existence of some formal power series *g*(*D*) with nonzero constant coefficient, such that *Hen*(*x*) = *g*(*D*)*xn*, is another equivalent to the statement that these polynomials form an Appell sequence.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] Since they are an Appell sequence, they are *a fortiori* a Sheffer sequence.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] The probabilist's Hermite polynomials defined above are orthogonal with respect to the standard normal probability distribution, whose density function is ${\frac {1}{\sqrt {2\pi }}}e^{-{\frac {x^{2}}{2}}},$ which has expected value 0 and variance 1.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] Scaling, one may analogously speak of **generalized Hermite polynomials** $\operatorname {He} _{n}^{[\alpha ]}(x)$ of variance α, where α is any positive number.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] (See the above section on Appell sequences and on the differential-operator representation, which leads to a ready derivation of it.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] Since polynomial sequences form a group under the operation of umbral composition, one may denote by $\operatorname {He} _{n}^{[-\alpha ]}(x)$ the sequence that is inverse to the one similarly denoted, but without the minus sign, and thus speak of Hermite polynomials of negative variance.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] For α > 0, the coefficients of $\operatorname {He} _{n}^{[-\alpha ]}(x)$ are just the absolute values of the corresponding coefficients of $\operatorname {He} _{n}^{[\alpha ]}(x)$ .
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] These arise as moments of normal probability distributions: The nth moment of the normal distribution with expected value μ and variance *σ*2 is $E[X^{n}]=\operatorname {He} _{n}^{[-\sigma ^{2}]}(\mu ),$ where X is a random variable with the specified normal distribution.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] Since these functions contain the square root of the weight function and have been scaled appropriately, they are orthonormal: $\int _{-\infty }^{\infty }\psi _{n}(x)\psi _{m}(x)\,dx=\delta _{nm},$ and they form an orthonormal basis of *L*2(**R**).
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] This fact is equivalent to the corresponding statement for Hermite polynomials (see above).
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] The Hermite functions satisfy the differential equation $\psi _{n}''(x)+\left(2n+1-x^{2}\right)\psi _{n}(x)=0.$ This equation is equivalent to the Schrödinger equation for a harmonic oscillator in quantum mechanics, so these functions are the eigenfunctions.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] This formula can be used in connection with the recurrence relations for *Hen* and *ψ**n* to calculate any derivative of the Hermite functions efficiently.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] The Hermite functions *ψ**n*(*x*) are a set of eigenfunctions of the continuous Fourier transform F.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] To see this, take the physicist's version of the generating function and multiply by *e*−⁠1/2⁠*x*2.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] The Hermite functions *ψn*(*x*) are thus an orthonormal basis of *L*2(**R**), which *diagonalizes the Fourier transform operator*.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] The Wigner distribution function of the nth-order Hermite function is related to the nth-order Laguerre polynomial.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] It is the standard paradigm of quantum mechanics in phase space.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] There are further relations between the two families of polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] In the Hermite polynomial *He**n*(*x*) of variance 1, the absolute value of the coefficient of *x**k* is the number of (unordered) partitions of an n-element set into k singletons and ⁠*n* − *k*/2⁠ (unordered) pairs.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] Equivalently, it is the number of involutions of an n-element set with precisely k fixed points, or in other words, the number of matchings in the complete graph on n vertices that leave k vertices uncovered (indeed, the Hermite polynomials are the matching polynomials of these graphs).
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] This combinatorial interpretation can be related to complete exponential Bell polynomials as $\operatorname {He} _{n}(x)=B_{n}(x,-1,0,\ldots ,0),$ where *x**i* = 0 for all *i* > 2.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] The function (*x*, *y*) → *E*(*x*, *y*; *u*) is the bivariate Gaussian probability density on **R**2, which is, when u is close to 1, very concentrated around the line *y* = *x*, and very spread out on that line.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/hermite-polynomials] It follows that $\sum _{n=0}^{\infty }u^{n}\langle f,\psi _{n}\rangle \langle \psi _{n},g\rangle =\iint E(x,y;u)f(x){\overline {g(y)}}\,dx\,dy\to \int f(x){\overline {g(x)}}\,dx=\langle f,g\rangle$ when *f* and *g* are continuous and compactly supported.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/jacobi-polynomials] In mathematics, **Jacobi polynomials** (occasionally called **hypergeometric polynomials**) $P_{n}^{(\alpha ,\beta )}(x)$ are a class of classical orthogonal polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/jacobi-polynomials] They are orthogonal with respect to the weight $(1-x)^{\alpha }(1+x)^{\beta }$ on the interval $[-1,1]$ .
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/jacobi-polynomials] The Gegenbauer polynomials, and thus also the Legendre, Zernike and Chebyshev polynomials, are special cases of the Jacobi polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/jacobi-polynomials] The Jacobi polynomials were introduced by Carl Gustav Jacob Jacobi.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/jacobi-polynomials] where $(\alpha +1)_{n}$ is Pochhammer's symbol (for the rising factorial).
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/jacobi-polynomials] The other solution involves the logarithm function.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/jacobi-polynomials] Bochner's theorem states that the Jacobi polynomials are uniquely characterized as polynomial solutions to Sturm–Liouville problems with polynomial coefficients.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/jacobi-polynomials] where $\Gamma (z)$ is the gamma function.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/jacobi-polynomials] The sum extends over all integer values of s for which the arguments of the factorials are nonnegative.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/jacobi-polynomials] As defined, they do not have unit norm with respect to the weight.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/jacobi-polynomials] This can be corrected by dividing by the square root of the right hand side of the equation above, when $n=m$ .
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/jacobi-polynomials] Since the Jacobi polynomials can be described in terms of the hypergeometric function, recurrences of the hypergeometric function give equivalent recurrences of the Jacobi polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/jacobi-polynomials] and the branch of square root is chosen so that $R(z,0)=1$ .
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/jacobi-polynomials] The Jacobi polynomials reduce to other classical polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/jacobi-polynomials] The Jacobi polynomials appear as the eigenfunctions of the Markov process on $[-1,+1]$ ${\mathcal {L}}=\left(1-x^{2}\right){\frac {\partial ^{2}}{\partial x^{2}}}+(px+q){\frac {\partial }{\partial x}}$ defined up to the time it hits the boundary.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/jacobi-polynomials] This is an analog of the Mehler kernel for Hermite polynomials, and the Hardy–Hille formula for Laguerre polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/jacobi-polynomials] Thus in this section we assume $\alpha ,\beta >-1$ by default.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/jacobi-polynomials] $\theta _{n,m}$ is strictly monotonically increasing with $\alpha$ and strictly monotonically decreasing with $\beta$ .
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/jacobi-polynomials] If $\alpha =\beta$ , and $m<n/2$ , then $\theta _{n,m}$ is strictly monotonically increasing with $\alpha$ .
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/jacobi-polynomials] uniformly for $m=1,2,\dots ,\left\lfloor cn\right\rfloor$ .
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/jacobi-polynomials] Fix an electric particle at +1 with charge ${\frac {1+\alpha }{2}}$ , and another particle at -1 with charge ${\frac {1+\beta }{2}}$ .
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/jacobi-polynomials] Then, place n electric particles with charge $+1$ .
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/jacobi-polynomials] The first relation states that the zeroes of $P_{n}^{(\alpha ,\beta )}$ are the equilibrium positions of the particles.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/jacobi-polynomials] As the zeroes specify the polynomial up to scaling, this provides an alternative way to uniquely characterize the Jacobi polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/jacobi-polynomials] The electrostatic interpretation allows many relations to be intuitively seen.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/jacobi-polynomials] Since the Stieltjes relation also exists for the Hermite polynomials and the Laguerre polynomials, by taking an appropriate limit of $\alpha ,\beta$ , the limit relations are derived.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/jacobi-polynomials] For example, for the Hermite polynomials, the zeros satisfy $-x_{i}+\sum _{1\leq j\leq n,i\neq j}{\frac {1}{x_{i}-x_{j}}}=0$ Thus, by taking $\alpha =\beta \to \infty$ limit, all the electric particles are forced into an infinitesimal neighborhood of the origin, where the field strength is linear.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/jacobi-polynomials] Then after scaling up the line, we obtain the same electrostatic configuration for the zeroes of Hermite polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/jacobi-polynomials] and the " O " term is uniform on the interval $[\varepsilon ,\pi -\varepsilon ]$ for every $\varepsilon >0$ .
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/jacobi-polynomials] The $M=1$ case is the above Darboux formula.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/jacobi-polynomials] where the limits are uniform for z in a bounded domain.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/jacobi-polynomials] The asymptotics outside $[-1,1]$ is less explicit.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/laguerre-polynomials] In mathematics, the **Laguerre polynomials**, named after Edmond Laguerre (1834–1886), are nontrivial solutions of **Laguerre's differential equation:** $xy''+(1-x)y'+ny=0,\ y=L(x)$ which is a second-order linear differential equation.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/laguerre-polynomials] This equation has nonsingular solutions only if n is a non-negative integer.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/laguerre-polynomials] Sometimes the name **Laguerre polynomials** is used for solutions of $xy''+(\alpha +1-x)y'+ny=0~.$ where n is still a non-negative integer.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/laguerre-polynomials] Then they are also named **generalized Laguerre polynomials**, as will be done here (alternatively **associated Laguerre polynomials** or, rarely, **Sonine polynomials**, after their inventor Nikolay Yakovlevich Sonin).
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/laguerre-polynomials] More generally, a **Laguerre function** is a solution when n is not necessarily a non-negative integer.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/laguerre-polynomials] The rook polynomials in combinatorics are more or less the same as Laguerre polynomials, up to elementary changes of variables.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/laguerre-polynomials] Further see the Tricomi–Carlitz polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/laguerre-polynomials] The Laguerre polynomials arise in quantum mechanics, in the radial part of the solution of the Schrödinger equation for a one-electron atom.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/laguerre-polynomials] They also describe the static Wigner functions of oscillator systems in quantum mechanics in phase space.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/laguerre-polynomials] They further enter in the quantum mechanics of the Morse potential and of the 3D isotropic harmonic oscillator.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/laguerre-polynomials] Physicists sometimes use a definition for the Laguerre polynomials that is larger by a factor of *n*! than the definition used here.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/laguerre-polynomials] For arbitrary real α the polynomial solutions of the differential equation $x\,y''+\left(\alpha +1-x\right)y'+n\,y=0$ are called **generalized Laguerre polynomials**, or **associated Laguerre polynomials**.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/laguerre-polynomials] This points to a special case (*α* = 0) of the formula above: for integer *α* = *k* the generalized polynomial may be written $L_{n}^{(k)}(x)=(-1)^{k}{\frac {d^{k}L_{n+k}(x)}{dx^{k}}},$ the shift by k sometimes causing confusion with the usual parenthesis notation for a derivative.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/laguerre-polynomials] which shows that *L**(α)* *n* is an eigenvector for the eigenvalue n.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/laguerre-polynomials] There is also a generalization for $x\in \mathbb {C} \setminus [0,\infty )$ .
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/laguerre-polynomials] Fejér's formula is a special case of Perron's formula with $M=1$ .
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/laguerre-polynomials] where $J_{\alpha }$ is a Bessel function of the first kind.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/laguerre-polynomials] Let $\operatorname {Ai}$ be the Airy function.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/laguerre-polynomials] Let $\alpha$ be arbitrary and real, $\epsilon$ and $\omega$ be positive and fixed.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/laguerre-polynomials] $j_{\alpha ,m}$ is the m -th positive zero of the Bessel function $J_{\alpha }(x)$ .
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/laguerre-polynomials] $a_{m}$ is the m -th zero of the Airy function $\operatorname {Ai} (x)$ , in descending order: $0>a_{1}>a_{2}>\cdots$ .
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/laguerre-polynomials] Thus in this section we assume $\alpha >-1$ by default.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/laguerre-polynomials] Fix an electric particle at origin with charge $+{\frac {\alpha +1}{2}}$ , and produce a constant electric field of strength $-{\frac {1}{2}}$ .
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/laguerre-polynomials] The first relation states that the zeroes of $L_{n}^{(\alpha )}$ are the equilibrium positions of the particles.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/laguerre-polynomials] As the zeroes specify the polynomial up to scaling, this provides an alternative way to uniquely characterize the Laguerre polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/laguerre-polynomials] In quantum mechanics the Schrödinger equation for the hydrogen-like atom is exactly solvable by separation of variables in spherical coordinates.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/laguerre-polynomials] The radial part of the wave function is a (generalized) Laguerre polynomial.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/laguerre-polynomials] Vibronic transitions in the Franck-Condon approximation can also be described using Laguerre polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/laguerre-polynomials] Because of this, the generalized Laguerre polynomials arise in the treatment of the quantum harmonic oscillator.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/laguerre-polynomials] The generalized Laguerre polynomials are used to describe the quantum wavefunction for hydrogen atom orbitals.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/laguerre-polynomials] where $\,_{1}F_{1}(a;b;x)$ is the confluent hypergeometric function.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/laguerre-polynomials] Generalized Laguerre polynomials are linked to umbral calculus by being Sheffer sequences for $D/(D-I)$ when multiplied by $n!$ .
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/orthogonal-polynomials] In mathematics, an **orthogonal polynomial sequence** is a family of polynomials such that any two different polynomials in the sequence are orthogonal to each other under some inner product.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/orthogonal-polynomials] The most widely used orthogonal polynomials are the classical orthogonal polynomials, consisting of the Hermite polynomials, the Laguerre polynomials and the Jacobi polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/orthogonal-polynomials] The Gegenbauer polynomials form the most important class of Jacobi polynomials; they include the Chebyshev polynomials and the Legendre polynomials as special cases.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/orthogonal-polynomials] These are frequently given by the Rodrigues' formula.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/orthogonal-polynomials] The field of orthogonal polynomials developed in the late 19th century from a study of continued fractions by P.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/orthogonal-polynomials] Some of the mathematicians who have worked on orthogonal polynomials include Gábor Szegő, Sergei Bernstein, Naum Akhiezer, Arthur Erdélyi, Yakov Geronimus, Wolfgang Hahn, Theodore Seio Chihara, Mourad Ismail, Waleed Al-Salam, Richard Askey, and Rehuel Lobatto.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/orthogonal-polynomials] Given any non-decreasing function *α* on the real numbers, we can define the Lebesgue–Stieltjes integral $\int f(x)\,d\alpha (x)$ of a function *f*.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/orthogonal-polynomials] This operation is a positive semidefinite inner product on the vector space of all polynomials, and is positive definite if the function α has an infinite number of points of growth.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/orthogonal-polynomials] It induces a notion of orthogonality in the usual way, namely that two polynomials are orthogonal if their inner product is zero.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/orthogonal-polynomials] In other words, the sequence is obtained from the sequence of monomials 1, *x*, *x*2, … by the Gram–Schmidt process with respect to this inner product.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/orthogonal-polynomials] Usually the sequence is required to be orthonormal, namely, $\langle P_{n},P_{n}\rangle =1,$ however, other normalisations are sometimes used.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/orthogonal-polynomials] Sometimes we have $d\alpha (x)=W(x)\,dx$ where $W:[x_{1},x_{2}]\to \mathbb {R}$ is a non-negative function with support on some interval [*x*1, *x*2] in the real line (where *x*1 = −∞ and *x*2 = ∞ are allowed).
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/orthogonal-polynomials] Such a *W* is called a **weight function**.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/orthogonal-polynomials] The most commonly used orthogonal polynomials are orthogonal for a measure with support in a real interval.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/orthogonal-polynomials] Discrete orthogonal polynomials are orthogonal with respect to some discrete measure.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/orthogonal-polynomials] Sometimes the measure has finite support, in which case the family of orthogonal polynomials is finite, rather than an infinite sequence.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/orthogonal-polynomials] The Racah polynomials are examples of discrete orthogonal polynomials, and include as special cases the Hahn polynomials and dual Hahn polynomials, which in turn include as special cases the Meixner polynomials, Krawtchouk polynomials, and Charlier polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/orthogonal-polynomials] Meixner classified all the orthogonal Sheffer sequences: there are only Hermite, Laguerre, Charlier, Meixner, and Meixner–Pollaczek.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/orthogonal-polynomials] In some sense Krawtchouk should be on this list too, but they are a finite sequence.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/orthogonal-polynomials] These six families correspond to the NEF-QVFs and are martingale polynomials for certain Lévy processes.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/orthogonal-polynomials] Sieved orthogonal polynomials, such as the sieved ultraspherical polynomials, sieved Jacobi polynomials, and sieved Pollaczek polynomials, have modified recurrence relations.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/orthogonal-polynomials] One can also consider orthogonal polynomials for some curve in the complex plane.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/orthogonal-polynomials] The most important case (other than real intervals) is when the curve is the unit circle, giving orthogonal polynomials on the unit circle, such as the Rogers–Szegő polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/orthogonal-polynomials] There are some families of orthogonal polynomials that are orthogonal on plane regions such as triangles or disks.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/orthogonal-polynomials] They can sometimes be written in terms of Jacobi polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/orthogonal-polynomials] For example, Zernike polynomials are orthogonal on the unit disk.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/orthogonal-polynomials] The advantage of orthogonality between different orders of Hermite polynomials is applied to Generalized frequency division multiplexing (GFDM) structure.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/orthogonal-polynomials] More than one symbol can be carried in each grid of time-frequency lattice.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/orthogonal-polynomials] Orthogonal polynomials of one variable defined by a non-negative measure on the real line have the following properties.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/orthogonal-polynomials] where the constants *c**n* are arbitrary (depend on the normalization of *P**n*).
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/orthogonal-polynomials] This comes directly from applying the Gram–Schmidt process to the monomials, imposing each polynomial to be orthogonal with respect to the previous ones.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/orthogonal-polynomials] For example, orthogonality with $P_{0}$ prescribes that $P_{1}$ must have the form $P_{1}(x)=c_{1}\left(x-{\frac {\langle P_{0},x\rangle P_{0}}{\langle P_{0},P_{0}\rangle }}\right)=c_{1}(x-m_{1}),$ which can be seen to be consistent with the previously given expression with the determinant.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/orthogonal-polynomials] The converse is also true; see Favard's theorem.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/orthogonal-polynomials] These recurrence relations are key for deriving properties of orthogonal polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/orthogonal-polynomials] If the measure d*α* is supported on an interval [*a*, *b*], all the zeros of *P**n* lie in [*a*, *b*].
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/orthogonal-polynomials] Moreover, the zeros have the following interlacing property: if *m* < *n*, there is a zero of *P**n* between any two zeros of *P**m*.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/orthogonal-polynomials] Foata, and others, combinatorial interpretations were found for all the classical orthogonal polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/orthogonal-polynomials] The Macdonald polynomials are orthogonal polynomials in several variables, depending on the choice of an affine root system.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/orthogonal-polynomials] They include many other families of multivariable orthogonal polynomials as special cases, including the Jack polynomials, the Hall–Littlewood polynomials, the Heckman–Opdam polynomials, and the Koornwinder polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/orthogonal-polynomials] The Askey–Wilson polynomials are the special case of Macdonald polynomials for a certain non-reduced root system of rank 1.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/orthogonal-polynomials] Multiple orthogonal polynomials are polynomials in one variable that are orthogonal with respect to a finite family of measures.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/orthogonal-polynomials] These are orthogonal polynomials with respect to a Sobolev inner product, i.e. an inner product with derivatives.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/orthogonal-polynomials] Including derivatives has big consequences for the polynomials, in general they no longer share some of the nice features of the classical orthogonal polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/orthogonal-polynomials] Orthogonal polynomials with matrices have either coefficients that are matrices or the indeterminate is a matrix.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/orthogonal-polynomials] Quantum polynomials or q-polynomials are the q-analogs of orthogonal polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/orthogonal-polynomials] Orthogonal polynomials can be defined as a vector basis set $P_{0},P_{1},P_{2},\dots$ of a symmetric bilinear form B on polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/orthogonal-polynomials] In the basis of the orthogonal polynomials, the bilinear form diagonalizes as $B(P_{i},P_{j})=B(P_{i},P_{i})\delta _{ij}$ .
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/orthogonal-polynomials] Similarly, given a nondegenerate skew-symmetric bilinear form on polynomials, we can find a pair of vector basis sets $P_{0},P_{1},P_{2},\dots$ and $Q_{0},Q_{1},Q_{2},\dots$ , such that the bilinear form skew-diagonalizes as $B(P_{i},Q_{j})=B(P_{i},Q_{i})\delta _{ij}$ .
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] In mathematics, the **Zernike polynomials** are a sequence of polynomials that are orthogonal on the unit disk.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] Named after optical physicist Frits Zernike, laureate of the 1953 Nobel Prize in Physics and the inventor of phase-contrast microscopy, they play important roles in various optics branches such as beam optics and imaging.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] There are even and odd Zernike polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] (odd function over the azimuthal angle $\varphi$ ) where *m* and *n* are nonnegative integers with *n ≥ m ≥ 0* (*m* = 0 for spherical Zernike polynomials), *$\varphi$* is the azimuthal angle, *ρ* is the radial distance $0\leq \rho \leq 1$ , and $R_{n}^{m}$ are the radial polynomials defined below.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] for even *n* − *m*, while it is 0 for odd *n* − *m*.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] The factor $\rho ^{n-2k}$ in the radial polynomial $R_{n}^{m}(\rho )$ may be expanded in a Bernstein basis of $b_{s,n/2}(\rho ^{2})$ for even n or $\rho$ times a function of $b_{s,(n-1)/2}(\rho ^{2})$ for odd n in the range $\lfloor n/2\rfloor -k\leq s\leq \lfloor n/2\rfloor$ .
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] where $\epsilon _{m}$ (sometimes called the Neumann factor because it frequently appears in conjunction with Bessel functions) is defined as *2* if $m=0$ and *1* if $m\neq 0$ .
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] where $d^{2}r=\rho \,d\rho \,d\varphi$ is an infinitesimal area element of the circular coordinate system (where $\rho$ is the Jacobian of a formula converting this coordinate system to Cartesian coordinate system), and where $n-l$ and $n'-l'$ are both even.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] Any sufficiently smooth real-valued phase field over the unit disk $G(\rho ,\varphi )$ can be represented in terms of its Zernike coefficients (odd and even), just as periodic functions find an orthogonal representation with the Fourier series.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] where the coefficients can be calculated using inner products.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] Alternatively, one can use the known values of phase function *G* on the circular grid to form a system of equations.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] The phase function is retrieved by the unknown-coefficient weighted product with (known values) of Zernike polynomial across the unit grid.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] Hence, coefficients can also be found by solving a linear system, for instance by matrix inversion.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] Fast algorithms to calculate the forward and inverse Zernike transform use symmetry properties of trigonometric functions, separability of radial and azimuthal parts of Zernike polynomials, and their rotational symmetries.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] where $(-1)^{l}$ could as well be written $(-1)^{n}$ because $n-l$ as even numbers are only cases to get non-vanishing Zernike polynomials.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] If *n* is odd, then *l* is also odd.) This property is sometimes used to categorize Zernike polynomials into even and odd polynomials in terms of their angular dependence.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] These equalities are easily seen since $R_{n}^{m}(\rho )$ with an odd (even) *m* contains only odd (even) powers to *ρ* (see examples of $R_{n}^{m}(\rho )$ below).
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] self-adjoint over the unit disk, with negative eigenvalues $L[Z_{n}^{m}]=-n(n+2)Z_{n}^{m}$ .
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] The main use of these recurrences is to avoid cancellation of digits that occurs for large n in the accumulation of the oscillatory binomial terms in the power series notation .
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] Applications often involve linear algebra, where an integral over a product of Zernike polynomials and some other factor builds matrix elements.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] To enumerate the rows and columns of these matrices by a single index, a conventional mapping of the two indices *n* and *m* to a single index *j* has been introduced by Noll.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] (In this section the m is the signed upper index of Z which may be positive or negative or zero.) The table of this association $Z_{n}^{m}\rightarrow Z_{j}$ starts as follows (sequence A176988 in the OEIS).
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] The Fringe indexing scheme is used in commercial optical design software and optical testing in, e.g., photolithography.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] where $\operatorname {sgn} m$ is the sign or signum function.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] The first 20 fringe numbers are listed below.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] Wyant uses the "Fringe" indexing scheme except it starts at 0 instead of 1 (subtract 1).
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] This method is commonly used including interferogram analysis software in Zygo interferometers and the open source software DFTFringe.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] The first few Zernike modes, at various indices, are shown below.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] In this table they are normalized differently than in the remaining sections: $\int _{0}^{2\pi }\int _{0}^{1}[Z_{j}(\rho ,\phi )]^{2}\cdot \rho \,d\rho \,d\phi =\pi$ , which is equivalent to $\operatorname {Var} (Z)_{\text{unit circle}}=1$ .
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] The functions are a basis defined over the circular support area, typically the pupil planes in classical optical imaging at visible and infrared wavelengths through systems of lenses and mirrors of finite diameter.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] Their advantages are the simple analytical properties inherited from the simplicity of the radial functions and the factorization in radial and azimuthal functions; this leads, for example, to closed-form expressions of the two-dimensional Fourier transform in terms of Bessel functions.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] Their disadvantage, in particular if high *n* are involved, is the unequal distribution of nodal lines over the unit disk, which introduces ringing effects near the perimeter $\rho \approx 1$ , which often leads attempts to define other orthogonal functions over the circular disk.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] In precision optical manufacturing, Zernike polynomials are used to characterize higher-order errors observed in interferometric analyses.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] In wavefront slope sensors like the Shack-Hartmann, Zernike coefficients of the wavefront can be obtained by fitting measured slopes with Zernike polynomial derivatives averaged over the sampling subapertures.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] In optometry and ophthalmology, Zernike polynomials are used to describe wavefront aberrations of the cornea or lens from an ideal spherical shape, which result in refraction errors.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] They are also commonly used in adaptive optics, where they can be used to characterize atmospheric distortion.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] Obvious applications for this are IR or visual astronomy and satellite imagery.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] Another application of the Zernike polynomials is found in the Extended Nijboer–Zernike theory of diffraction and aberrations.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] Zernike polynomials are widely used as basis functions of image moments.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] Since Zernike polynomials are orthogonal to each other, Zernike moments can represent properties of an image with no redundancy or overlap of information between the moments.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] Although Zernike moments are significantly dependent on the scaling and the translation of the object in a region of interest (ROI), their magnitudes are independent of the rotation angle of the object.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] Thus, they can be utilized to extract features from images that describe the shape characteristics of an object.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] For instance, Zernike moments are utilized as shape descriptors to classify benign and malignant breast masses or the surface of vibrating disks.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] Zernike Moments also have been used to quantify shape of osteosarcoma cancer cell lines in single cell level.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] Moreover, Zernike moments have been used for early detection of Alzheimer's disease by extracting discriminative information from the MR images of Alzheimer's disease, mild cognitive impairment, and healthy groups.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] The concept translates to higher dimensions *D* if multinomials $x_{1}^{i}x_{2}^{j}\cdots x_{D}^{k}$ in Cartesian coordinates are converted to hyperspherical coordinates, $\rho ^{s},s\leq D$ , multiplied by a product of Jacobi polynomials of the angular variables.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] In $D=3$ dimensions, the angular variables are spherical harmonics, for example.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] (Note that a factor ${\sqrt {2n+D}}$ is absorbed in the definition of *R* here, whereas in $D=2$ the normalization is chosen slightly differently.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] For $D=3$ this was proposed by Deng and Gwo.
[src:orthogonal-polynomials/zernike-polynomials] The case for $D=2$ was published by Chong et al.
